    skillLevel: "Application",
    question: "A SOC 1 report differs from a SOC 2 report in that SOC 1:",
    options: ["Provides no useful information for auditors","Is only for government entities","Reports on controls at a service organization relevant to user entities' internal control over financial reporting (ICFR), while SOC 2 reports on controls related to security, availability, processing integrity, confidentiality, or privacy (Trust Services Criteria)","Covers cybersecurity only"],
    correctAnswer: 2,
    explanation: "SOC (System and Organization Controls) reports: SOC 1 (AT-C §320): Controls relevant to ICFR. Used by the user entity's auditor in a financial statement audit. Replaces the old SAS 70 report. SOC 2 (AT-C §205 + Trust Services Criteria): Controls related to the 5 Trust Services Criteria — Security (always included), Availability, Processing Integrity, Confidentiality, Privacy. Used for management, regulators, business partners. SOC 3 (AT-C §205): Same as SOC 2 but a general-use report (shorter, no detailed testing). Type 1: design of controls at a point in time. Type 2: design AND operating effectiveness over a period.",
