    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "AU-C 570.16 requires the auditor to evaluate management's plans for feasibility and effectiveness. For financing plans, the auditor should: (1) evaluate whether the financing is probable — are there signed commitments, term sheets, or credit agreements? Mere intentions are not sufficient; (2) assess whether the entity can meet the terms and conditions of the financing; (3) consider whether the amount of financing is sufficient to address the entity's needs; (4) evaluate whether the overall plan effectively mitigates the going concern doubt. Other plan elements (disposing of assets, reducing costs, restructuring debt) are similarly evaluated for feasibility. If management's plans do not adequately mitigate the doubt, the auditor's report must include an emphasis-of-matter paragraph.",
