    difficulty: "easy",
    skillLevel: "Remembering and Understanding",
    question: "Under AICPA quality control standards, audit documentation for non-issuers should generally be retained for:",
    options: ["One year","Five years from the report release date","Indefinitely","Three years"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "SQCS (Statement on Quality Control Standards) requires non-issuer audit documentation to be retained for a period sufficient to meet the needs of the firm and satisfy legal and regulatory retention requirements — generally five years from the report release date. For SEC issuers under PCAOB standards, the retention period is seven years. During the retention period, documentation should be maintained securely with appropriate access controls. After the retention period, the firm may destroy the documentation in accordance with its policies. Some firms retain documentation longer due to litigation risk or specialized industry requirements.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - One year is insufficient under AICPA quality control standards for non-issuers; the retention period is significantly longer to allow for peer review and potential legal challenges.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - AICPA quality control standards generally require audit documentation for non-issuers to be retained for five years from the report release date to meet the needs of the firm and satisfy legal and regulatory requirements.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - Retaining audit documentation indefinitely is not required by AICPA quality control standards and would create unnecessary storage and administrative burdens for the firm.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - Three years is not the correct retention period. AICPA quality control standards require a longer retention period of five years from the report release date for non-issuers.",
    },
    educational: "Audit documentation retention is crucial for quality control and legal defense. The retention period allows for peer reviews, inspections, and potential litigation. Proper documentation supports the audit opinion and demonstrates adherence to professional standards.",
    examTip: "Remember the 5-year rule for non-issuers and the 7-year rule for issuers when dealing with audit documentation retention periods.",
    memoryAid: "Think 'Non-issuers Need Five' to remember the five-year retention period for non-issuers.",
    reference: "SQCS; AU-C 230",
