    explanation: "AU-C §300 (Planning): Overall audit strategy: high-level document that sets: (1) Scope of the audit, (2) Timing of the audit (interim vs. year-end procedures), (3) Direction — overall approach, significant areas, use of specialists, resource allocation, supervision. Audit plan: more detailed than the strategy — describes: (1) Nature, timing, and extent of risk assessment procedures, (2) Nature, timing, and extent of further audit procedures (tests of controls and substantive procedures) at the assertion level, (3) Other planned procedures required by GAAS. Both may be updated and changed as the audit progresses. Planning is iterative — it continues throughout the engagement.",
