    educational: "Independence is a cornerstone of auditing, ensuring objectivity and unbiased opinions. Direct financial interests create an inherent conflict, as the CPA's personal financial well-being could be influenced by the audit client's performance. Therefore, any direct financial interest, regardless of size, impairs independence.",
    examTip: "Remember that direct financial interests are a bright-line rule: any amount impairs independence, unlike indirect interests where materiality matters.",
    memoryAid: "Direct = Disqualifies. Any direct financial interest immediately disqualifies a CPA from performing the audit.",
    reference: "AICPA ET §1.240.010-.020",
