    explanation: "AU-C 315.A41 through A44 explains that business risks — risks resulting from conditions, events, or circumstances that could adversely affect the entity's ability to achieve its objectives — can lead to financial statement misstatements. For example: aggressive growth targets (business risk) may pressure management to overstate revenue (fraud risk); declining industry (business risk) may impair inventories or goodwill (misstatement risk); new regulatory requirements (business risk) may affect accounting treatments. The auditor identifies business risks to understand how they might translate into risks of material misstatement at the assertion level.",
