    subtopic: "Variables Sampling",
    difficulty: "hard",
    skillLevel: "Analysis",
    question: "The auditor uses monetary unit sampling (MUS) to test accounts receivable. MUS is particularly effective for detecting:",
    options: ["Understatement of balances","Overstatement of balances, because larger items (higher dollar amounts) have a proportionally higher chance of selection","Classification errors only","Timing differences only"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Monetary unit sampling (MUS, also called probability-proportional-to-size sampling) treats each individual dollar as a sampling unit. This means every dollar has an equal chance of selection, and larger accounts automatically have a higher probability of inclusion. This makes MUS particularly effective for testing existence/overstatement — large overstatements are likely to be caught because the overstated dollars have a higher selection probability. MUS is less effective for understatement testing because understated items have fewer dollars and a lower chance of selection. MUS is commonly used for receivables, inventory, and other asset accounts.",
