    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "AU-C 600.A4 identifies two bases for component significance: (1) Individual financial significance — a component that represents a substantial portion of the group's assets, revenue, or other key measures (e.g., a subsidiary that contributes 25% of group revenue); (2) Significant risk — a component that, due to its nature or circumstances, is likely to include significant risks of material misstatement to the group (e.g., a newly acquired entity, a component in a high-risk jurisdiction, or one with unusual transactions). Significant components receive more extensive audit attention — typically a full audit or specified procedures.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Having any revenue doesn't automatically make a component significant for audit purposes; significance is determined by its relative size or risk to the group.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - A component is significant if it's individually financially important to the group (large portion of revenue/assets) OR if it poses a significant risk of material misstatement to the group's financials due to its nature or circumstances.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - The component operating in the same country as the parent is irrelevant to its significance; significance is based on financial impact or risk.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - Using the same accounting framework doesn't determine significance. A small component using the same framework is still not significant.",
    },
    educational: "When auditing group financial statements, auditors must identify significant components. Significance is determined by either the component's financial importance to the group as a whole or the risk of material misstatement it poses. Auditors will then tailor their audit procedures based on the significance of each component.",
    examTip: "Focus on the words 'individual financial significance' and 'significant risk' when determining component significance on the exam.",
    memoryAid: "Think of 'Size' and 'Risk' - a component is significant if it's large in size relative to the group or poses a significant risk.",
    reference: "AU-C 600.A4 through A6",
