    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Under AU-C 610.15 through 17, the external auditor considers: (1) the nature and scope of internal audit work performed (does it address areas relevant to the external audit?); (2) the assessed risk of material misstatement — the higher the risk, the less the external auditor should rely on internal auditor work; (3) the degree of subjectivity in evaluating evidence — less reliance is appropriate for areas involving significant judgment; (4) the previously assessed objectivity, competence, and systematic approach of the internal audit function. For areas of low risk involving objective evidence (e.g., testing routine transactions), more use is appropriate. For areas of high risk or significant judgment, the external auditor should perform procedures directly.",
