      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - An Emphasis-of-Matter paragraph highlights a matter already adequately presented in the financial statements that is crucial for users to properly understand the financial position, performance, or cash flows of the entity. It doesn't change the auditor's opinion, but draws attention to something important.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - A qualified opinion arises when there is a material misstatement or scope limitation that is not pervasive. This results in a modification of the opinion paragraph itself, not the addition of an Emphasis-of-Matter paragraph.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - While a going concern uncertainty *can* be disclosed in an Emphasis-of-Matter paragraph if adequately disclosed in the financial statements and the auditor is comfortable with management's plans, it's not the *only* reason for an Emphasis-of-Matter paragraph. If substantial doubt exists and is not adequately disclosed, a modified opinion is required.",
