    explanation: "Cutoff: transactions recorded in proper period. For sales: compare shipping dates (FOB terms) to invoice dates near year-end. Test several days before and after cutoff. Proper transfer of title timing.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Reviewing the sales budget is useful for analytical procedures and identifying potential areas of risk, but it doesn't directly verify the accuracy of sales cutoff.",
      1: "Why option B is WRONG - Confirming all sales is impractical and inefficient; cutoff testing focuses on transactions around year-end.",
      2: "Why option C is CORRECT - Comparing shipping document dates to sales invoice dates around year-end directly tests whether sales were recorded in the correct accounting period, ensuring revenue is recognized when the goods are shipped and title transfers.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - Recalculating all invoices is a test of accuracy, not cutoff; it verifies the mathematical correctness of the invoices, not the timing of revenue recognition.",
    },
    educational: "Cutoff testing ensures that transactions are recorded in the correct accounting period. For sales revenue, this means verifying that revenue is recognized when the goods are shipped and title transfers to the buyer, typically indicated by the shipping date. Auditors examine transactions occurring shortly before and after year-end to ensure proper timing.",
    examTip: "When you see 'cutoff testing,' immediately think about the dates of key documents like shipping documents and invoices, and whether they align with the accounting period.",
    memoryAid: "SCO: Shipping date, CutOff",
