    correctAnswer: 3,
    explanation: "Written representations confirm management's responsibility for the financial statements and acknowledge their oral responses to audit inquiries. They complement other audit evidence but do not replace substantive tests. Representations alone are not sufficient audit evidence.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Management representations are not a substitute for performing substantive testing procedures. Auditors must perform tests of details and analytical procedures to gather sufficient appropriate audit evidence.",
      1: "Why option B is WRONG - Management representations complement other audit evidence but cannot substitute for it. Auditors need corroborating evidence to support management's claims.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - While documentation is important, the primary purpose of management representations is not simply to satisfy legal requirements. They serve a broader purpose of confirming management's responsibilities.",
      3: "Why option D is CORRECT - Management representations serve to confirm management's responsibility for the fair presentation of the financial statements and to document their responses to inquiries made during the audit. This provides important evidence about management's integrity and understanding of their responsibilities.",
    },
    educational: "Management representations are written statements from management to the auditor, documenting key assertions and understandings. They are obtained at the end of the audit to reinforce oral representations and clarify management's responsibilities regarding the financial statements. These representations help the auditor assess the reliability of other audit evidence and management's integrity.",
    examTip: "On the exam, remember that management representations are corroborative, not conclusive, evidence; they support other audit work but don't replace it.",
