      1: "Why option B is WRONG - Tolerable deviation rate and acceptable risk of overreliance are inversely related; decreasing the acceptable risk of overreliance would necessitate a *lower* tolerable deviation rate, not a higher one.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - A lower acceptable risk of overreliance necessitates a *larger* sample size to provide more assurance, not a smaller one.",
      3: "Why option D is CORRECT - A lower acceptable risk of overreliance means the auditor is willing to accept less risk of incorrectly concluding that controls are effective. To reduce this risk, the auditor needs to examine a larger sample to gather more evidence.",
