    question: "During the audit of Johnson & Co., the auditor identified a heightened risk of management override of internal controls due to the CEO's significant bonus being tied to achieving a 15% year-over-year revenue growth target. The auditor already planned to perform substantive analytical procedures on revenue accounts. Which of the following additional audit procedures would be *most* effective in directly addressing this specific fraud risk related to management override?",
    options: ["Perform surprise inventory counts at all locations to detect potential inventory manipulation used to inflate revenue.","Examine journal entries and other adjustments, particularly those made close to year-end, and investigate any unusual or unsupported items.","Review the company's whistleblower hotline reports for any allegations of financial reporting misconduct.","Increase the sample size for testing of sales invoices to ensure proper revenue recognition."],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Examining journal entries and other adjustments, particularly those made near year-end, is the most effective procedure to directly address the risk of management override of controls. Management override often involves making inappropriate adjustments to financial records to achieve desired results. AU-C 240.39 specifically directs the auditor to consider this procedure when responding to fraud risks related to management override. While the other options are valid audit procedures, they are not as directly responsive to the specific risk of management manipulating journal entries to inflate revenue.",
