    subtopic: "Inquiry of Management and Others",
    difficulty: "medium",
    skillLevel: "Analysis",
    question: "During the planning phase of an audit, the auditor is required to make inquiries to management and others within the entity regarding the risk of fraud. Which of the following statements concerning these inquiries is most accurate?",
    options: ["The auditor should direct inquiries only to management personnel who have direct responsibility for the financial reporting process.","The auditor should inquire of the audit committee, internal auditors, and other employees about their views of the risks of fraud and whether they have knowledge of any fraud.","The auditor should only make inquiries if the initial risk assessment procedures indicate a high risk of material misstatement due to fraud.","The auditor is not required to make inquiries if management is deemed to have high integrity and a strong ethical tone."],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "The auditor is required to make inquiries of management, the audit committee, internal auditors (if any), and other employees about their views of the risks of fraud and whether they have knowledge of any fraud. This broad approach helps gather diverse perspectives and uncover potential fraud risks that management might not be aware of. AU-C 240.20-.22",
